## Report Outline: Local LLMs

**1. Introduction**
   - Define Local LLMs (running on enterprise-owned PCs, workstations, servers, edge devices)
   - Contrast with cloud API-based deployment
   - Thesis: Real-time inference on billion-parameter models now fits on consumer/enterprise hardware

**2. Why Go Local**
   - **Lower data exposure** — keep proprietary data in-house, avoid API leakage
   - **Better control** — full governance over model versioning, updates, rollout
   - **Offline / low-latency operation** — no network dependency, suitable for edge/remote sites
   - **Easier customization** — fine-tune for internal workflows without vendor lock-in

**3. Hardware Feasibility**
   - Consumer-grade GPUs (e.g., NVIDIA RTX 3060 12GB, RTX 4080/5080) running billion-parameter models in real time
   - Quantization breakthroughs (GGUF, 4/8-bit) shrinking model footprint
   - Memory constraints: 7B models need ~4-8GB VRAM at 4-bit; 70B needs multi-GPU or CPU offloading

**4. Open-Source Models Driving Adoption**
   - Llama 3 / 3.1 family (8B, 70B)
   - Mistral, Mixtral, Phi series
   - Qwen, Gemma, and other alternatives

**5. Inference & Deployment**
   - llama.cpp (GGUF inference, cross-platform)
   - Ollama, vLLM, Text Generation Inference
   - Containerized on-prem deployments (Kubernetes, Docker)

**6. Use Cases in Enterprise**
   - Internal knowledge search / Q&A
   - Document drafting, code assistance
   - Edge inference for industrial / field applications
   - Compliance-sensitive workflows (healthcare, finance, government)

**7. Limitations & Risks**
   - Capability gap vs. frontier cloud models
   - Hardware cost at scale
   - Maintenance burden (updates, monitoring, prompt engineering)

**8. Future Outlook**
   - Continued hardware improvements (more VRAM, better memory bandwidth)
   - Smaller models closing the capability gap
   - Hybrid cloud-on-prem architectures

